You cannot absolutely use the `switch` statement on `String` literals. It can be only used on bytes, chars or Enum types.

As you are designing an Operation based calculator, I strongly recommend using an `Enum` type labeled `Operation` defining an abstract method for calculation method matter with constant specific implementations:

&lt;!-- language: lang-java --&gt;

    public enum Operation
    {
      ADD
          {
            @Override
            double apply(double argOne, double argTwo)
            {
              return argOne + argTwo;
            }
          },
      SUBSTRUCT
          {
            @Override
            double apply(double argOne, double argTwo)
            {
              return argOne - argTwo;
            }
          },
      DEVIDE
          {
            @Override
            double apply(double argOne, double argTwo)
            {
              return argOne / argTwo;
            }
          },
      MULTIPLY
          {
            @Override
            double apply(double argOne, double argTwo)
            {
              return argOne * argTwo;
            }
          };
    
      abstract double apply(double argOne, double argTwo);
    }

Note that the above Enum type will let you gain in both flexibility in terms you can add as much operations as you want without hurting other software components, and you can use it as a `switch` label:

